A clear distinction must be made between the theological use of the word, which we have in this treatise‚ not quite for the first time in Christian litera- ture, and the philosophical use, which is purely modern. Of the latter it need only be said that the belief in a Persona] God is contrasted with Pantheism and with any form of Theism which represents God as Un- knowable, as Impersonal Law, as the Infinite, and so forth.

It has been said, with a certain truth, ‘Personality, as we conceive it, is essentially a limitation and a relation. Our own personality is presented to us as relative and li1nited3 and it is from that presentation that all our representative notions of personality are derived.
